  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Celia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Caelia</i>, feminine form of the old Roman family name <i>Caelius</i> (of uncertain origin, probably a derivative of <i>caelum</i> ‘heaven’). The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was introduced to the English-speaking world as the name of a character in  Shakespeare's  As You Like It. It was popularized in the 1940s by the actress  Celia Johnson  (  1908–82 ). This name is sometimes taken as a short form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Metilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Celia Metilda de Bradshagh was born in 1122, in Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Trollope, was 28 and her mother, Elizabeth Coleby de Trollope, was 62. She had at least 1 son with William De Bradshagh. She died in 1161, in France, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1122–1161":"1122–1161","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1160–1192":"1160–1192","1094–1173":"1094–1173","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1135":"1135","1122":"1122","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1192":"1192","Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1122–1161":"1122–1161","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1160–1192":"1160–1192","1094–1173":"1094–1173","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1135":"1135","1122":"1122","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1192":"1192","Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1122–1161":"1122–1161","1135–Male":"1135–Décédé","1160–1192":"1160–1192","1094–1173":"1094–1173","1060–Female":"1060–Décédée","1135":"1135","1122":"1122","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1192":"1192","Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Celia Metilda de Bradshagh est née en 1122, à Doddington, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William de Trollope, avait 28 a